==English==

===Etymology===
{{webster}}

From [[w:Old English language|Old English]] plien, [[w:French language|French]] [[plier]] (meaning ''to [[fold]], to [[bend]]), from [[w:Latin|Latin]] [[plicare]]; akin to [[w:Greek language|Greek]] , [[w:German language|German]] [[flechten]]. Compare with [[apply]], [[complex]], [[display]], [[duplicity]], [[employ]], [[exploit]], [[implicate]], [[plait]], [[pliant]], [[flax]].

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/plaɪ/}}
* {{rhymes|aɪ}}

===Noun===
'''ply''' (plural '''plies''')

# A [[layer]] of material. (''two-ply toilet paper'')
# Short for [[plywood]].
# In two-player sequential games, a ply refers to one turn taken by one of the players: ''A ply in chess is a half-move. (From: [http://en.wikipedia.org/Ply_(game_theory) Wikipedia, Ply (game theory)])''

===Verb===
{{en-verb|plies|plying|plied}}

#{{transitive}} To [[work]] at [[diligent]]ly.  (''ply one's trade'')
#{{transitive}} To [[travel]] over [[regular]]ly. (''ply the seven seas'')
#{{transitive}} To [[use]] [[vigorous]]ly or [[wield]]. (''ply a sword'')

